Last year, the government scrapped public order laws which empowered policemen to take action against people dressed "indecently", and allowed for non-Muslims to consume alcohol.
It also decriminalised conversion from Islam.
Those reforms triggered street protests slamming the decisions as "anti-Islamic."
"Islamists usually play on the religious chord which is a very sensitive subject in the Sudanese society," said Mirghani, who is also editor-in-chief of Al Tayyar daily.
"The transitional government tends to overlook this aspect, and it should be more careful -- because disputes between Islamists and liberals will persist in full force." On Wednesday, Sudan said an Ethiopian military aircraft flew over the Sudanese-Ethiopian border and warned of "dangerous ramifications". Sudan and Ethiopia have been mired in a border conflict. Mr Museveni leads with 4,340,134 million votes against NUP presidential candidate, Bobi Wineâ€™s 2,164,347 votes. Earlier on Friday, the Ugandan opposition leader said the election had seen "widespread fraud and violence". Ugandan opposition leader rejects early results which gave President Yoweri Museveni a wide lead as a "joke".